Life at Its Limits: Microbes in the Seabed Survive on Far Less Energy Than Shown Ever Before </h1><div class="entry-tags clearfix"><span>TOPICS:</span><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/bacteria/" rel="tag">Bacteria</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/biodiversity/" rel="tag">Biodiversity</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/gfz-german-research-center-for-geosciences/" rel="tag">GFZ German Research Center for Geosciences</a><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/tag/oceanography/" rel="tag">Oceanography</a></div> </header><p class="entry-meta">
<span class="entry-by">By</span> <span class="entry-meta-author vcard author">GFZ German Research Center for Geosciences</span>
<span class="entry-meta-date updated">August 5, 2020</span>
</p>
<div class="entry-content clearfix">
<div id="attachment_91584" style="width: 787px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea.jpg"><img aria-describedby="caption-attachment-91584" loading="lazy" class="size-large wp-image-91584" src="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-777x437.jpg" alt="Heatflow Beneath the Sea" width="777" height="437" srcset="https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-777x437.jpg 777w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-400x225.jpg 400w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-768x432.jpg 768w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-1536x864.jpg 1536w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-180x101.jpg 180w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-260x146.jpg 260w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-373x210.jpg 373w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea-120x67.jpg 120w, https://scitechdaily.com/images/Heatflow-Beneath-the-Sea.jpg 1800w" sizes="(max-width: 777px) 100vw, 777px" /></a><p id="caption-attachment-91584" class="wp-caption-text">Photograph taken from ALVIN, a manned deep-ocean research submersible, taking sediment cores at the ocean floor of the Dorado Outcrop in 2014. Credit: Geoff Wheat, NSF OCE 1130146, and the National Deep Submergence Facility. Credit: Geoff Wheat, NSF OCE 1130146, and the National Deep Submergence Facility</p></div>
<p><strong>All life needs energy. Where there is not enough energy available, there can be no life. But how much is enough?</strong></p>
<p>A new study led by James Bradley of the German Research Centre for Geosciences GFZ and Queen Mary University of London provides a surprising answer: Microbes in the seabed survive on far less energy than has been shown ever before. The international team is publishing its results in the journal&nbsp;<em>Science Advances</em>.</p>
<p>James Bradley, who started this work at the University of Southern California (USA) and continued it at GFZ, says: &ldquo;When we think about the nature of life on Earth, we see plants, animals, microscopic algae and bacteria thriving on the Earth&rsquo;s surface and in the oceans &mdash; constantly active, growing and reproducing. But here we show that an entire biosphere of microorganisms &mdash; as many cells as are found in all the Earth&rsquo;s soils or oceans &mdash; has barely enough energy to survive. Many of them simply exist in a mostly inactive state. They do not grow, do not divide and do not develop further. These microbes are not dead, but use far less energy than previously thought to survive.&rdquo;</p>
